Assigment 5¶

This assigment will be graded if everything works well. I will run the script as once and everything should be done without errors and mistakes. I should be able to run your scripts in my computer and get all the results. USE RELATIVE PATHS. An error or exception or anything that breaks the code will means NO GRADE (0). Additionally, you are not able to modify any file handly. It also means NO GRADE (0). Comment everything you think will help others read your script. We expect 0 errors using GitHub. Everything will be graded!

ASK EVERYTHING! WE ARE HERE TO HELP YOU!

In this path .._data\sbs\B_RawData\bancos you will find scraped data from this link. We get all the information of the last available day of every each month.

  1. Generate a function called import_data_sbs_banks that take as arguments start_month, start_year, end_month and end_year. This function should be able to import the files in .._data\sbs\B_RawData\bancos taking into consideration these arguments. Additionally, it should work if it is only given the first two arguments (start_mont, start_year). The function should returns a nested dictionary. The main key must be year and second key must be month. The values should be the dataframes.

1.0. Show all data from SBS¶

1.1. Load data in a big container¶

In [2]:
# The next for loop basically reads each excel file found in "data" and creates a dictionary with the keys being date, month, year and the data per se.

data = {}
for file in sbs_files:
    # Read excel file and save in a provisional df
    df = pd.read_excel(file)
    # Use regex pattern to detect the day that was published
    patron = r'\d{1,2}_(\d{1,2})_(\d{4})'
    # Include date
    date = pd.to_datetime(re.search(patron, file).group(0), format = "%d_%m_%Y")
    df["date"] = date
    data[re.search(patron, file).group(0)] = {'date': date, 'month': re.search(patron, file).group(1), 'year': re.search(patron, file).group(2), 'data': df}
    #print(df)
In [3]:
# Show the result
data

2.0. General structure of the function and data import logic for a single month and year¶

In [4]:
# The next function works so that the user can easily filter information from the SBS based on a given date. The user needs to
# input a starting month and a starting year (the end month and end year being optional).

import pandas as pd
from datetime import datetime

def import_data_sbs_banks(start_month, start_year, end_month=None, end_year=None): #4 arguments, the last two being optional
    if end_month is None: 
        end_month = start_month
    if end_year is None:
        end_year = start_year

    start_date = datetime(start_year, start_month, 1) #We create  "datetime" obj for the start date and end date, using start_year, start_month, end_date and end_month 
    end_date = datetime(end_year, end_month, 1)

    filtered_data = {} #empty dictionary that will save filtered data organized by year and month 
    for key, value in data.items(): #Se está filtrando los datos del diccionario existente data 
        file_date = value['date']
        if start_date <= file_date <= end_date:
            year = value['year']
            month = value['month']
            df = value['data']

            if year not in filtered_data:
                filtered_data[year] = {}
            if month not in filtered_data[year]:
                filtered_data[year][month] = df

    return filtered_data
In [5]:
# Usage example
# Input to obtain data from January 2021 until June 2021
datos_filtrados = import_data_sbs_banks(1, 2021, 6, 2021)

# Now 'datos_filtrados' contains a dictionary with data from the given months

# To access data from March 2021
datos_marzo_2021 = datos_filtrados.get("2021", {}).get("3", None)

# Now 'datos_marzo_2021' is a DataFrame with data from March 2021,
# or None in case there is no data for the given month and date
